#compdef neovate
# =============================================================================
# neovate — Neovate AI's "Code Agent to enhance your development"
#           — a TypeScript-Node CLI for the Neovate Code AI
#           assistant: an interactive (or headless) agent for
#           code generation, bug fixing, code review, test
#           generation, refactoring, with multi-model support
#           (Claude, GPT, Gemini, etc.), MCP (Model Context
#           Protocol) integration, session resume, ACP (Agent
#           Client Protocol) mode, and plugin extensibility.
#           Distinguishing from claude-code (the official
#           Anthropic CLI), aider, cursor-cli, and other AI
#           code agents by:
#             - INTERACTIVE + HEADLESS MODES — default is
#               interactive REPL with streaming output;
#               `-q/--quiet` runs in non-interactive mode
#               suitable for piping into scripts / CI
#             - 10 SUBCOMMANDS via yargs-parser:
#                 * acp                — run as ACP (Agent Client
#                                        Protocol) agent
#                 * call               — call NodeBridge handlers
#                                        directly
#                 * config             — manage configuration
#                 * commit             — commit changes to repo
#                 * log [file]         — view session logs in HTML
#                 * mcp                — manage MCP servers
#                 * run                — run a command
#                 * skill              — manage skills
#                 * update             — check for and apply
#                                        updates
#                 * workspace          — manage workspaces
#             - MULTI-MODEL ROLE ASSIGNMENT — beyond a single
#               `--model`, neovate accepts:
#                 * --plan-model       — model used for planning
#                 * --small-model      — model used for quick ops
#                 * --vision-model     — model used for image
#                                        tasks
#               allowing different tiers (e.g., Sonnet for
#               coding, Haiku for tool-pick, GPT-4V for image
#               analysis)
#             - SESSION RESUME via -r/--resume SESSION_ID +
#               -c/--continue (continue latest session); each
#               session persisted with full message history
#             - MCP SERVER INTEGRATION — `--mcp-config` accepts
#               JSON string with mcpServers object OR file path
#               to MCP config; neovate launches MCP servers and
#               wires their tools/resources/prompts into the
#               agent
#             - 3 OUTPUT FORMATS via --output-format:
#                 * text         — plain text
#                 * stream-json  — newline-delimited JSON events
#                 * json         — single JSON output
#             - 3 APPROVAL MODES via --approval-mode:
#                 * default      — prompt before each tool call
#                 * autoEdit     — auto-approve edits, prompt
#                                  other tools
#                 * yolo         — auto-approve everything
#             - TOOL CONFIGURATION via --tools JSON — enable/
#               disable individual tools (write, bash, etc.)
#                 neovate --tools '{"write":false}'
#                 neovate --tools '{"bash":false,"write":false}'
#             - PLUGIN SYSTEM — --plugin and --plugin-dir
#               (multiple) load TypeScript/JavaScript plugins
#               that extend neovate's capabilities
#             - SKILLS via `neovate skill` — package up reusable
#               agent capabilities; skills are first-class
#               primitives in neovate's architecture
#             - WORKSPACES via `neovate workspace` — multi-
#               project workspace management with shared
#               config and session history
#             - WEBSOCKET TRANSPORT via `ws` — neovate uses
#               `ws` for the ACP (Agent Client Protocol)
#               WebSocket server endpoint that external editors
#               (VS Code, Neovim, IntelliJ) connect to;
#               bidirectional streaming agent events
#             - ASCII ART branding on startup (PRODUCT_ASCII_ART
#               constant)
#             - NPM REGISTRY UPDATE CHECKING — built-in upgrade
#               flow checking registry.npmjs.org for newer
#               versions
#           Used by: developers running AI-assisted coding
#           workflows that need MCP integration, multi-model
#           configurations, session persistence, and external
#           editor integration via ACP, and as a reference
#           implementation of `ws` + yargs-parser + MCP +
#           NodeBridge + plugin-architecture composition in
#           TypeScript-Node CLIs.
#
# Author:  Neovate AI (neovate.ai) — AI tooling startup.
#          Active development through 2026; current version
#          0.28.5.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/neovateai/neovate-code
#          https://github.com/neovateai/neovate-code/blob/main/src/cli.ts
#          https://github.com/neovateai/neovate-code/blob/main/src/index.ts
#          https://github.com/neovateai/neovate-code/blob/main/package.json
# CLI:     src/cli.ts + src/index.ts — uses yargs-parser (low-
#          level argv parser; not a full framework).  Headline
#          library: **ws** (yargs-parser is documented across
#          many Node completions; ws is the new variant being
#          documented here, completing Axis 18 three-language
#          symmetry across Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: ws (https://github.com/websockets/ws —
#          "Simple to use, blazing fast and thoroughly tested
#           WebSocket client and server for Node.js" — Einar
#           Otto Stangvik (creator) + Luigi Pinca (current lead
#           maintainer) + 200+ contributors.  Distinct from
#           tokio-tungstenite (R657, Rust Axis 18 opener) and
#           gorilla/websocket (R658, Go Axis 18 expansion) by
#           being:
#              1. RFC 6455 WEBSOCKET PROTOCOL — same protocol as
#                 tungstenite + gorilla but Node.js-idiomatic:
#                   import { WebSocketServer, WebSocket } from 'ws'
#                   // Server:
#                   const wss = new WebSocketServer({ port: 8080 })
#                   wss.on('connection', (sock) => {
#                     sock.on('message', (msg) => sock.send(msg))
#                   })
#                   // Client:
#                   const sock = new WebSocket('wss://api.example.com')
#                   sock.on('open', () => sock.send('hello'))
#                   sock.on('message', (data) => console.log(data))
#              2. NATIVE STREAMS API — WebSocket extends Node.js
#                 EventEmitter + supports Duplex stream semantics
#                 via createWebSocketStream(ws).  Integrates
#                 with Node's stream pipeline:
#                   import { createWebSocketStream } from 'ws'
#                   const duplex = createWebSocketStream(ws)
#                   duplex.pipe(fs.createWriteStream('out.bin'))
#              3. EVENTEMITTER API — open / message / close /
#                 error / ping / pong / unexpected-response /
#                 upgrade events.  Distinct from tungstenite's
#                 Stream<Item=Message> and gorilla's
#                 ReadMessage()/WriteMessage() blocking calls.
#                 Idiomatic for Node.js event-driven runtime.
#              4. PERMESSAGE-DEFLATE BY DEFAULT — ws 7+ enables
#                 permessage-deflate compression by default
#                 (configurable via { perMessageDeflate: false
#                 } option).  Distinct from tungstenite +
#                 gorilla which require opt-in features.
#              5. BROWSER-COMPATIBLE WEBSOCKET API — ws's
#                 WebSocket class matches the W3C/WHATWG
#                 WebSocket browser API exactly (addEventListener
#                 events 'open' / 'message' / 'close' / 'error'
#                 also work in addition to EventEmitter 'on').
#                 This enables isomorphic code targeting both
#                 browser and Node.
#              6. NO TLS WRAPPING — uses Node's https.Agent for
#                 wss:// connections; TLS comes from Node's
#                 tls module.  Distinct from tungstenite's
#                 Cargo-feature TLS backend choice; same
#                 stdlib-TLS approach as gorilla.
#              7. ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES — ws has NO
#                 production npm dependencies (development-only
#                 utilities).  Distinct from tungstenite + gorilla
#                 (which have a few transitive deps each).
#              8. CHILD WORKER UPGRADE — ws's `verifyClient`
#                 callback can route upgrade requests to
#                 different handlers; useful for multi-tenant
#                 servers.
#              9. STRICT MODE — strictMode option enforces RFC
#                 6455 frame validation (close codes, UTF-8
#                 validity in text frames, control frame size
#                 limits).
#             10. WEBSOCKETS-ORG / LPINCA ECOSYSTEM — Luigi Pinca
#                 maintains ws + a constellation of related
#                 packages (engine.io, socket.io build on top).)
# License: MIT (ws); MIT (neovate)
